    "kit": {
      "info": {
        "contact": {
          "url": "https://viacep.com.br/"
        },
        "description": "ViaCEP is a free web service that allows users to query Brazilian postal codes (CEPs) and retrieve address information in JSON or XML format. The service supports AJAX requests and facilitates easy integration for address autofill and validation in applications.",
        "servers": [
          {
            "description": "Production server",
            "url": "https://viacep.com.br/ws"
          }
        ],
        "title": "ViaCEP Address Lookup",
        "version": "1.0.0",
        "tagline": "Look up Brazilian postal codes (CEP) and resolve them to street, neighborhood, city and state",
        "homepage": "https://viacep.com.br/",
        "docs_url": "https://viacep.com.br/",
        "license_short": "Free public web service; no redistribution of the database, no commercial resale",
        "license_md": "- Free to call from applications; no API key required.\n- The underlying CEP database may not be redistributed or sold.\n- Heavy bulk usage to validate local databases may result in automatic, indefinite blocking.\n- No formal open-source licence is published; treat the service itself as the licensed artefact.",
        "about_md": "[ViaCEP](https://viacep.com.br/) is a free Brazilian web service for looking up postal codes (*Código de Endereçamento Postal*, or CEP) and resolving them to a structured postal address. It is widely used in Brazilian e-commerce and government forms for address autofill and validation.\n\nWhat you get from the API:\n\n- Forward lookup by 8-digit CEP: `GET /ws/{cep}/json/` returns the street (`logradouro`), complement, neighborhood (`bairro`), city (`localidade`), state (`uf`), region (`regiao`), and codes such as IBGE, GIA, DDD and SIAFI.\n- Reverse lookup by address: `GET /ws/{uf}/{cidade}/{logradouro}/json/` returns up to 50 matching CEPs (UF, city, and street each need at least 3 characters).\n- Alternate response formats: JSON, XML and JSONP (with a `callback` parameter).\n\nOperational notes: the service responds over HTTPS with CORS enabled, so it can be called directly from browsers. Invalid or non-existent CEPs return `{\"erro\": \"true\"}` rather than an HTTP error; malformed requests return `400 Bad Request`. There is no published rate limit, but the operators warn that bulk validation of local databases can trigger an automatic block.",
        "entity_desc": {
          "cep_lookup": "A Brazilian postal code (CEP) and its resolved address; forward lookup at `/ws/{cep}/json/` and reverse lookup by state, city and street at `/ws/{uf}/{cidade}/{logradouro}/json/`."
        },
